# Angular component workflow

Always scaffold components with the Angular CLI first. Never hand-create `.component.ts`, `.html`, `.scss`, or `.spec.ts` files.

## Required command

```bash
npx ng generate component <path>/<name> --flat --defaults
```

For lazy-loaded route components and the app shell, also pass `--export-default`.

Project defaults (from `angular.json`): standalone, OnPush, scss, `.component.*` filenames.

Examples:

```bash
# App shell
npx ng generate component app --flat --export-default --defaults

# Route-level feature component (flat files in feature folder)
npx ng generate component features/portfolio/portfolio --flat --export-default --defaults

# Child component inside a feature (flat files in same folder)
npx ng generate component features/market-watch/connection-status --flat --defaults
```

## After scaffolding only

1. Edit the generated `.component.ts`, `.component.html`, `.component.scss`, and `.component.spec.ts` — no inline `template`/`styles`.
2. Use BEM class names in HTML/SCSS.
3. In specs that use NgRx, use `provideMockStore({ initialState: mockAppState })` from `src/app/state/testing/mock-app-state.ts`.
4. Wire routes/imports only after the component files exist.

## Do not

- Create component files manually without running `ng g c`
- Use `--skip-tests`, `--inline-template`, or `--inline-style`
- Overwrite existing components with `--force` unless the user explicitly asks to regenerate
